body:
@zack3000 if you are sure that the log-in password didn't changed you don't have to reset the password. unfortunately oc5 can't decide this so you always get the same error message, oc6 will be better in detecting different error states and produce a more detailed and accurate error message in such cases.

as you can read in this thread the key gets encrypted during log-in and stored in the users session. for some reasons it looks like for some users the sessions loses the key after some time. i couldn't reproduce this until now and have no idea why this should happen. but as a first try i would suggest to try to log out and log-in again if this happens the next time. 

would be great if you could check if it is really the session who loses the key. if the encryption works the key should be stored in your server session file. for a default debian installation this file is located in  /var/lib/php5. if it stop working have another look at the session file to check if the key is gone. to isolate the problem it would be good to know what you did exactly before the encryption stopped working.

@schiesbn 

i think the problem is when you log in then close the browser without logging out, and then try to access files by just opening the browser again. like if the key is lost when you close the browser, and you have to re-login to get it again. 

if you just close the browser and donâ´t log out, i always get that message when i try to access my files again. at least if i wait a few minutes between my attempts.
